## For Microsoft 365 Co-Pilot, evaluate Research capability for functional requirement category of Data Integration where Requirement is Data parsing and support for various data formats (e.g., Primary: Word Doc, PDF; Secondary: PPT, Excel; Optional: JSON, XML, CSV, SQL).

### Response: Microsoft 365 Copilot demonstrates robust capabilities in parsing and supporting various data formats:

Available: Copilot can currently parse and analyze Word documents, PDFs, PowerPoint files, and Excel spreadsheets. It can summarize long documents in Word, analyze spreadsheet data and find trends in Excel, and convert unstructured text into structured formats like tables. These capabilities are actively in use.

Planned: Copilot in OneDrive will soon allow users to select multiple files (up to five) for AI-generated summaries or comparisons without manually opening them. This feature is announced as "coming soon".

The research also indicates support for additional formats: Available: Copilot can work with text, HTML, CSV, XML, OpenDocument, EPUB, RTF, Apple iWork, JSON, YAML, and LaTeX files.

Copilot's ability to handle various formats stems from its integration with the Microsoft Graph and the Semantic Index, which allows it to understand and process content across different file types within the Microsoft 365 ecosystem.

While SQL parsing is not explicitly mentioned, Copilot's planned integration with Power Platform connectors (coming in 2025) suggests future capabilities for working with database content.

Citations: [Microsoft 365 Copilot - Service Descriptions | Microsoft Learn] [Introducing Microsoft 365 Copilot – your copilot for work - The Official Microsoft Blog]

